The CV profiles of all electrodes were measured in a voltage range of 0–0.6 V at a scan rate of 5 mV/s (Fig. 4
                        a). The capacitive behavior of the Ni foam substrate is negligible due to its very low capacitance. All electrodes exhibited pseudocapacitive behavior with symmetric redox curves. Notably, the CD2/CuO-NiO revealed the largest CV curve area, corresponding to the highest capacitance of 635F/g at a scan rate of 5 mV/s, compared to 301, 468, 470, and 310 F g−1 from Ni-doped Cu2(CO3)(OH)2, CuO-NiO, CD1/CuO-NiO, and CD3/CuO-NiO, respectively. Remarkably, the CD2/CuO-NiO had a higher specific capacitance by 211 and 136 %, compared to the Ni-doped Cu2(CO3)(OH)2 and pure CuO-NiO, respectively. This indicates the strong impact of the CDs on the charge storage/transfer of electrodes. The GCD measurements of all electrodes were performed at a current density of 5 A g−1 (Fig. S3a). A specific capacitance of 218, 318, 379, 545, and 255 F g−1 was obtained for the Ni-doped Cu2(CO3)(OH)2, CuO-NiO, CD1/CuO-NiO, CD2/CuO-NiO, and CD3/CuO-NiO electrodes, respectively. The specific capacitances from the GCD results are consistent with those obtained from the CV results (Fig. S3b). The EIS was then utilized to explore the series resistance of the electrodes, which can be employed to determine the capacitive properties of the electrodes [37]. As shown in the Nyquist plot (Fig. 4b), the Ni-doped Cu2(CO3)(OH)2 exhibited a small charge transfer resistance (Rct) of 0.85 Ω, whereas the others displayed only the solution resistance (Rs) with neglibile Rct. This finding revealed that the charge transfer process is outstanding in the CuO-NiO, compared to the Ni-doped Cu2(CO3)(OH)2. The CuO-NiO, CD1/CuO-NiO, CD2/CuO-NiO, and CD3/CuO-NiO demonstrated the Rs of 0.93, 0.93, 0.87, and 0.94 Ω, respectively. This indicates that 20 mg of CDs is optimum for minimizing the solution resistance. Interestingly, at the low frequency region, the CD2/CuO-NiO had the most vertical line compared to the other electrodes, signifying that it has favorable capacitive behaviors, which led to a high specific capacitance. The Bode plots of all electrodes demonstrate the relationship between the phase angle and log frequency (Fig. S4). The phase angles at the y-intercepts are related to the capacitive properties and supercapacitor performance [38]. The phase angles of Ni-doped Cu2(CO3)(OH)2, CuO-NiO, CD1/CuO-NiO, CD2/CuO-NiO, and CD3/CuO-NiO electrodes are −56.0°, −56.7°, −59.6°, −66.0°, and −56.3°, respectively, which correspond well to their specific capacitance. The CD2/CuO-NiO had the phase angles closest to −90°, an ideal value for an excellent supercapacitor. This confirms the enhancing role of the CDs to the CuO-NiO-based electrodes. Fig. 4c illustrates the CV profiles of CD2/CuO-NiO at various scan rates, in which a pair of redox peaks are observed, suggesting the characteristic faradaic pseudocapacitance. The cathodic peak at 0.21 V and the anodic peak at 0.38 V indicate the combined contribution of CuO and NiO to charge storage via redox processes [39]. The impacts of scan rate on the specific capacitance of the CD2/CuO-NiO were investigated. The anodic peaks shifted to higher potentials as the scan rate was increased, whereas the cathodic peaks shifted to lower potentials. In the course of a redox reaction, rate-limited ion diffusion and charge transfer processes cause these shifts [40]. In addition, the log of current (i) versus the log of scan rates (v) was plotted (Fig. S5) to confirm the charge transfer behavior. The b-value was obtained from the slope of the plot. When the b-value is between 0.5 and 1, electron transfer occurs via diffusion control, whereas a b-value of 1 indicates electron transfer via an electrical double-layer [41]. The b-value of the CD2/CuO-NiO electrode was found to be 0.6011, confirming its pseudocapacitive behavior. At all current densities, the GCD profiles of the CD2/CuO-NiO (Fig. 4d) clearly revealed the plateau shape of the discharge curves, verifying the Faradaic properties of charge storage [40,42]. These consequences are also consistent with the apparent redox peaks in the CV curves. The calculated specific capacitances of the CD2/CuO-NiO are 682, 668, 633, 545, 493, 459, 435, and 428 F g−1 at the current density of 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, and 9 A g−1, respectively, revealing an outstanding rate capability of 63 % for a 4.5-fold increase in current density. In addition, the prepared CD2/CuO-NiO provided the highest specific capacitance than the previous reports based on CuO or NiO-based supercapacitors (Table 1
                        ). Furthermore, the cycling stability of CuO-NiO was investigated and compared to that of CuO-NiO embedded with CDs (CD2/CuO-NiO). As shown in Fig. S7, the capacitance retention of the CuO-NiO supercapacitor is 60 % after 10,000 charge–discharge cycles, whereas the CD2/CuO-NiO supercapacitor shows a gradual decrease in capacitance retention, stabilizing at 76 % after 10,000 cycles. This improvement is attributed to the in-situ and binder-free synthesis of the CuO-NiO electrode with embedded CDs, which significantly enhances electrode adhesion, structural integrity, and stability. The presence of CDs improves the interfacial bonding within the electrode material, reducing the risk of material degradation and loss of active sites during prolonged cycling [43]. These results demonstrate that the incorporation of CDs not only enhances specific capacitance but also improves cycling stability in supercapacitors. The novel use of CDs with CuO-NiO thus presents a promising strategy for fabricating high-performance, cost-effective supercapacitors with simple preparation methods.
